Features

X Convert File Audio can be used in a very basic way for example for the extraction of musical tracks from a cd-audio which can be converted to different formats such as ogg, flac, mp3, ... but X Convert File Audio can also be used to manipulate, transform and arrange the contents of these files as you see fit.

Below, a description of the tabs will help explain the functionalities.


Installation with binary files:

XCFA is developed under the Debian distribution and the packages necessary for its installation are therefore naturally of the DEB type. My personal repository allows you to use the latest version and its recognition requires modifying the /etc/apt/sources.list file on your system in which you will need to include the following lines:

# CLE GPG XCFA
#
# wget http://download.tuxfamily.org/xcfaudio/download/xcfaudio.key.asc -O - | apt-key add -
# WHERE
# gpg --keyserver subkeys.pgp.net --recv 00B21603DD5C7A79
# gpg --export --armor 00B21603DD5C7A79 | apt-key add -
#
# XCFA STABLE
#
# deb http://download.tuxfamily.org/xcfaudio/xcfa/ dev contrib
# deb-src http://download.tuxfamily.org/xcfaudio/xcfa/ dev contrib
#
# XCFA BETA
#
deb http://download.tuxfamily.org/xcfaudio/xcfa_beta/ dev contrib
deb-src http://download.tuxfamily.org/xcfaudio/xcfa_beta/ dev contrib

Installation with source files:

Get the latest version of XCFA from one of these two addresses
  • Version stable
  • Version beta
Then use these commands from a text shell window, adapting of course to the version number you just downloaded: 
$ tar xvfz ./xcfa-4.3.4~beta0.tar.gz
$ cd xcfa-4.3.4~beta0/
$ ./configure --prefix=/usr
If necessary, you will have to install the missing libraries, for example: 
***
*** Please, install libasound2-dev development headers 
***
then repeat the command: 
$ ./configure --prefix=/usr
When everything is ok: 
=================================================================
  Configuration for xcfa 4.3.4~beta0 :
=================================================================

  Host System Type ................ : x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu ( Linux-based system )
  HosName .........................: debian64
  Compiler ........................ : gcc 
  Linker .......................... : -lm -lvte -lcurl -lpthread -lasound -ltag_c 
  NLS/gettext ..................... : yes

  GTHREAD version ................. : 2.24.2
  LIBCURL version ................. : 7.21.0
  VTE version ..................... : 0.24.3
  Debug mode g .................... : no
  Debug mode pg ................... : no
  WITH ANSI COMPILATE ............. : no
  CFLAGS .......................... : -Wall -O3 -D_REENTRANT -DLinux -Wl,--export-dynamic
  INSTALL ......................... : /usr/bin/xcfa

  Options parameters:
  -------------------
  by default:
  	--disable-debug                             No debug support
  	--disable-debug-pg                          No debug support with gprof
  	--disable-ansi                              No define ansi for probleme compilate
  Options is:
  	--enable-debug      #define DEBUG 1         Define for debug: -g
  	--enable-debug-pg   #define DEBUG_PG 1      Define for debug support with gprof: -pg  
  	--enable-ansi       #define ENABLE_ANSI 1   Define With ansi compilate

  Now type 'make' to build xcfa 4.3.4~beta0,
  and then type (under root) 'make install' for installation.
You can finally continue with the command: 
$ make
And perform a first test with: 
$ ./src/xcfa
Installation on the system in administrator mode: 
# make install

The xcfa_install_all_x_x_x program is accompanied by (brief!) Documentation that I invite you to consult.
This program, which can be used on the command line (from a text shell window), allows you to complement the programs used by xcfa and which are absent from your distribution.

  • Download the latest version.
  • Make the executable with:
    # chmod +x ./nom_du_programme.pl
  • For demo in user mode:
    $ ./nom_du_programme.pl
  • For actual installation of missing programs:
    # ./nom_du_programme.pl

Options and additional information

  • The "normalize" option allows you to manage the common volume of audio files before recording.
  • It is possible to rework the quality of wav files according to several criteria: the frequency in hertz, the number of channels and the number of bits.
  • A modification of the bitrates of mp3 and ogg files is available from the "Mp3-Ogg" tab.
  • XCFA can also go to the Web to retrieve information about the audio CD being processed.
  • The creation of CD cover is possible.
  • XCFA was developed with Glade2 and uses the Gtk-2, Glib-2, etc ... libraries.

First use

Use either a shell window: 
$ xcfa
... or from the desktop menu in the "Sound and video" section, click on the XCFA icon. At the first launch, go to the "Options" tab and make the necessary settings:
  • Use your package manager to install missing software
  • Destination of checkouts / conversions

Some keyboard shortcuts to know

  • Ctrl + A
    Global selection
  • Suppror Del
    Delete the current selection

Description

  • The menu
    Exits XCFA.
    Allows settings for the tabs: DVD, CD and Files.
    Allows access to the box: About.

  • "DVD " tab

    This tab was created in close collaboration with @Dzef and @Shankarius.
    This tab allows you to rip and convert DVD tracks as Wav type files.
    Possibility of file normalization.
    Extractions and conversions are intended to be directed to Wav format with 2 channels but a conversion to a number of channels equivalent to the source file remains possible.
    A choice of mixing as well at the level of the "Sub" as of the "ambiences" is possible for a source of 4, 5 and 6 channels towards 2 channels.


  • "CD" tab

    You can change the settings from: Preferences -> CD .

    • Bug ICEDAX
      The specific 'icedax' encoding replaces all accented characters with an underscore! Go to this page and read the patch_icedax.txt file which explains what to do while waiting for a modification of the icedax code by its author to whom I have sent a modification request . Since version 4.0.4 ~ beta6, the modified icedax file is no longer needed.



    Since you have installed all the necessary programs for the different types of conversions, you just have to select the appropriate box and then click on: Extract .


    Extraction with cdparanoia or icedax.


    Extraction with cdparanoia in expert mode.
    XCFA tries to take over some interesting features of 'rubyripper':
    Two extractions of the same track are made then compared.
    Invalid segments will be replayed up to four times if necessary and then validated if possible.


    Two very good reference articles to help you in your choices:

    • Ogg Vorbis explained by @Shankarius.
    • Standardization under XCFA explained by @Dzef.

    Before an extraction and conversion operation, you have the possibility here to modify the content of the tags of your future files.

    Multiple possibilities for arranging the titles of your files.


    You can create a single file for the formats: WAV, FLAC, OGG and MPC from at least two previously selected extractions.

  • "Files" tab


    The choice of the file (s) is made via the Import button or by a Drag And Drop action.
    Do not forget to select the destination of future operations.
    The Clean button will act on the selected lines.

    • Files

      • A green selection indicates that the options on the Preferences tab are taken into account.
      An orange selection indicates that the expert options on the Preferences tab have been taken into account: your personal parameters can be defined.


      Four possibilities for normalization are possible:
      Peak / Album
      Maximum amplification of the volume for a group of files while respecting the differences in levels between each of them.
      Peak
      Maximum volume amplification for each file.
      Mix (scan) rms / album
      Adjustment of the average volume for a group of files while respecting the differences in average levels between each of them.
      Fix (scan) rms
      Average volume adjustment for each file.

      A very well designed page by @Dzef will give you all the useful explanations .

      Unlike normalization, the functionality of ReplayGain will only apply dynamic modification (tags) to files.
      Above a table for the modifications of quantifications.

  • Onglet "Split"

    A specific version of 'Split' has been developed with the invaluable help of @Dzef as well as the participation of ML.

    1. Importation

      The import concerns the WAV, FLAC, OGG, MP3, APE, WMA types which are converted to the WAV format at 44110 Hertz, 2 channels and 16 bits if necessary.
      As soon as a file is imported, XCFA searches for and marks the tracks.
      A range is validated by a change to '<~ -50 dB'.
      The import of a file is done by clicking on the 'Import' button giving access to a dialog or a drag / drop (Drag And Drop).
      The destination of the split operation can be redirected with an action on the 'Destination' button of the files'.

    2. Timeline

      The chronological bar gives time information on the waveform.
      The movement of the mouse cursor is displayed in red color.

    3. Selector bar and waveform

      The number of editable ranges is in the interval [1 .. 99].
      A click on the central button allows the creation of a new range.
      The selection of a range is made with a left click on the selector bar or by using the mouse wheel or from the contextual menu.
      The deletion of a range is done either on the keyboard with the key: 'Del' (or 'Del') or from a contextual menu that can be called by pressing the right button of the mouse.
      The start of a track is identified by the color orange and the end of a track is green.
      THEMoving the start or end selectors is done by superimposing the mouse cursor on the selector and keeping the left mouse button pressed.
      A minimum period of 4 seconds separates the start and end selectors.
      The addition of a selection is done by clicking the middle mouse button.
      The e zoom is done with the key kept pressed Control + click the center (wheel) mouse ( Ctrl + Scroll).

    4. Lecture audio / Production cue / Production Split

      A lsa is used for audio playback.
      The layback 5 seconds at the beginning or end of range.
      The continuous layback with possibility of displacement of the reading head.



  • "Pocket" tab

    • The code for the cover uses the functions of the Cairo library.
    No more waiting time for image refresh.
    File backups are in the formats: PNG, PostScript and PDF.
    Importing images can be done by DragAndDrop (drag and drop).
    Give free rein to your imagination and xcfa will do the rest ...
    In short, intuitive use will allow you to discover it easily.


  • "Preferences" tab

    • This tab allows very fine adjustment of the parameters.

Error encountered with Mplayer

  • The message:
    "Requested audio codec family [mpg123] (afm = mpg123) not available. Enable it at compilation."
    can be bypassed by adding to the file ~ / .mplayer / config the line:
    ac = -ffmp3float
    This info. was given to me by @bandit
  • mplayer must be installed and not mplayer2
